Fix regression causing all taxonomies to be returned for all typesWhile the taxonomies routes are now type-independent, the post typenroutes (e.g. /posts/types/post) return embedded taxonomy objects forneach taxonomy associated with that type. Removing the types argumentnfrom the get_taxonomies method caused a regression where ALLntaxonomies would be returned for any post type endpoint.n

Add test for add_taxonomy_data regressionThis adds a test to verify that get_taxonomies only returns taxonomiesnfor the provided post type if a type is passed into the function. Reinstate $types parameter for back-compat with 1.0$types is only necessary in `get_taxonomies` and `add_taxonomy_data`;nhowever, we need to leave it in the argumentss list for ALL methods innorder to avoid breaking any plugins built to interoperate with v1.0.nnget_taxonomy (singular), prepare_taxonomy, get_terms, get_term,nand prepare_term should all have their $type parameter removed in 2.0.n

Add new methods for base /taxonomies routes & update testsBecause the new /taxonomies route have no $type parameter, and $typencannot be removed without breaking back-compat, we need to add a newnset of route methods for the new, correct /taxonomies routes. Tonminimize confusion, the old route method names were left as is, andnnew methods added for each method which had previously taken a $type.nAll the old methods are marked @deprecated and have a @see referencento their successors.nnNew methods:nn- `get_taxonomy` now wraps the new `get_taxonomy_object`n- `prepare_taxonomy` now wraps the new `prepare_taxonomy_object`n- `get_terms` now wraps the new `get_taxonomy_terms`n- `get_term` now wraps the new `get_taxonomy_terms`n- `prepare_term` now wraps the new `prepare_taxonomy_term`nnThe existing unit tests were changed to point to these new route methods.n

Embed associated post type records in Taxonomy objectsThis is the first pass at embedding a list of associated post types inntaxonomy records, as described in #197. Types are NOT embedded if theynwould be added to a taxonomy record that is itself embedded.nn@rmccue has proposed changing how the $_in_taxonomy behavior works tonuse a $context variable, as in other methods; this commit should benconsidered a work-in-progress until he has signed off on it.n

Add ?{taxonomy}_exclude= query parameterThis mirrors our existing support for `?{taxonomy}=` filtering in thenposts controller (which allows querying for only records with arenassociated with any of the provided term IDs for the specified taxonomy)nby adding an equivalent `_exclude` variant to list IDs of terms for whichnassociated posts should NOT be returned.nnFor categories _e.g._, `/wp/v2/posts?categories[]=7&categories[]=9` wouldnreturn a post in categories 7 _or_ 9; this PR adds support for the inversenquery `?categories_exclude[]=7&categories_exclude[]=9`, meaning onlynreturn posts that are associated with neither category 7 or category 9.nn`{term base}_exclude` is supported for any taxonomy registered with the API,nand is set within the same loop inside the controller as the existing termninclude parameters.nnWhile using the existing categories filter with a negative number wasnconsidered ([see slack discussion][slack-disc]), `{base}_exclude` maintainsnmore consistency with other exclusion filters present in the API such asn`parent_exclude` (and is much easier to implement, to boot).nn[slack-disc]: https://wordpress.slack.com/archives/core-restapi/p1475525429004981n
